Part I - Airlines Delay¶

by Priyangka Roy¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains scheduled and actual departure and arrival times that were reported by certified U.S. air carriers. In this project, last 10 years data is used for analysis. Original dataset holds at least 1% of the scheduled passenger revenues.

  • Description of the dataset can be found in this link: https://www.transtats.bts.gov/DatabaseInfo.asp?QO_VQ=EFD&Yv0x=D
  • Dataset can be downloaded from this link: https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/HG7NV7

In [11]:
# looks like there's a long tail in the distribution, so let's put it on a log scale instead
log_binsize = 0.025
bins = 10 ** np.arange(2.4, np.log10(df['arr_flights'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize) #10 ** ...: This part takes each value from the generated array and calculates 10 raised to the power of that value. This effectively transforms the sequence of exponents into a sequence of actual bin edges on a logarithmic scale.  

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'arr_flights', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4], [500, '1k', '2k', '5k', '10k', '20k'])
plt.xlabel('arr_flights')
plt.show()

Observations¶

  • Plotting original data for arr_flights seemed long tailed with most of values towards low values. Used log scale to plot better visualization but it still shows this variable has kind of expontially decreasing toward right kind of distribution.

Question: Number of flight per Year and Month?¶

In [14]:
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 12))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.6)
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
n_points = df.shape[0]
for i, j in enumerate(['year', 'month']):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i+1)
    sb.countplot(data=df, y=j, color=base_color);

    gen_counts = df[j].value_counts()
    locs, labels = plt.yticks() # get the current tick locations and labels
    # loop through each pair of locations and labels
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
        count = gen_counts[int(label.get_text())]
        pct_string = f'{100*count/n_points:0.1f}%'
        # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
        plt.text(0.92*count, loc, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'w')

    plt.title(f'Number of Flights per {j}');

Observations:¶

  • Highest number of flights was in the year of 2019
  • Highest number of flights was in the month in the month of January

Flight delay reasons and how much they contribute to the number of delayed flights¶

  • We also see that the weather is not the main reason for delays. Weather only contributes to 5.20% of the delays.
In [15]:
# storing different type of delay sums in variables
wethear_ct_sum= df['weather_delay'].sum()
nas_ct_sum= df['nas_delay'].sum()
carrier_ct_sum= df['carrier_delay'].sum()
security_ct_sum =df['security_delay'].sum()
late_aircraft_sum = df['late_aircraft_delay'].sum()

# total delays
num_of_overall_cancelation = wethear_ct_sum+nas_ct_sum+carrier_ct_sum+security_ct_sum+late_aircraft_sum

# percentage of delays
wethear_ct_sum=(wethear_ct_sum/num_of_overall_cancelation)*100
nas_ct_sum=(nas_ct_sum/num_of_overall_cancelation)*100
carrier_ct_sum=(carrier_ct_sum/num_of_overall_cancelation)*100
security_ct_sum=(security_ct_sum/num_of_overall_cancelation)*100
late_aircraft_sum=(late_aircraft_sum/num_of_overall_cancelation)*100

# plotting to show percentage of delays
X = ['weather delays' , 'nas delays','carrier delays','late air craft','security delays']
Y = [wethear_ct_sum, nas_ct_sum,carrier_ct_sum,late_aircraft_sum,security_ct_sum]
plt.pie(Y, labels=X ,colors=['#59a14f','#4e79a7','#4e79a7','#4e79a7','#4e79a7'], explode=[0.4,0,0,0,0],  autopct='%1.2f%%')
plt.title('Contribution of each Delay reason to overall delays')
plt.show()

Flight cancellation reasons and how much they contribute to the number of canceled flights¶

  • We can clearly see that a late air craft arival is the main reason why flight get canceled and not weather or secuirity problems. Infact weather contributes with only 3.4% and secuirity cancelation contributes with only 0.2%

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • For variable arr_flights the distribution seemed left skewed after log transformation.
  • For variable arr_delay the distribution seemed normal after log transformation. The delay time is about 20 hour.
  • For variable weather_delay the distribution looked left skewed after log transformation.
  • For variable year and month horizontal bar plot was drawn to show the percentage of number of flights. 2019 was the year that had highest number of flights with 12.3% and January was the month with highest number of flights (9.2%).

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • arr_delay was converted into hour to show ticks in x-axis for explanation purposes.

Monthly trends for weather delays¶

In [17]:
# Function to label the plots
def label_plots(xL,yL,title):
    '''
    This function plots the labels of a figure.
    
    Args:
    xL : label for x-axis
    yL : label for y-axis
    title: label for title
    '''
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xL)
    plt.ylabel(yL)
In [18]:
df_weather = df[['month', 'weather_delay']].groupby('month').sum().reset_index()

df_weather.plot(x='month', y='weather_delay' )
#call the function to label the figure
label_plots('Month','Number of weather delays','Number of weather delays per month')
plt.xticks(list(range(0,13,1)))
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • It demonstrates that weather delays occur in both winter and summer. It demonstrates how hot weather can cause aircraft delays. Flights can be delayed not just by rain and snow, but also by hot temperatures.

Percentage of flight delays compare to total flights¶

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 16))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.6)
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
n_points = df.shape[0]
for i, j in enumerate(['year', 'month']):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i+1)

    # get counts of total and delayed flights
    delayed_flights = df[df['arr_delay']>=15]
    gen_counts = df[j].value_counts()
    delayed_gen_counts = delayed_flights[j].value_counts()

    # plot stacked bar charts (reindex or use barplot's order)
    gen_counts.sort_index().plot.barh(label='Total', width=.6)
    delayed_gen_counts.sort_index().plot.barh(label='Delayed', color='darkorange')

    locs, labels = plt.yticks() # get the current tick locations and labels
    # loop through each pair of locations and labels
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
        count = gen_counts[int(label.get_text())]
        delayed_count = delayed_gen_counts[int(label.get_text())]
        pct_string = f'{100*delayed_count/count:0.1f}%'
        # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
        plt.text(0.30*count, loc, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'w')

    plt.legend(framealpha = 0.5, fancybox=True);
    plt.title(f'Number of Flights per {j}');

Observations:¶

  • Highest percentage of flight delayed in the year of 2014 (98.3%) and highest percentage of fligt delayed in the month of February (97.3%)

Total Delays by Airline¶

In [23]:
# Calculate the sum of each type of delay for each airline
delay_columns = ['arr_delay', 'carrier_delay', 'weather_delay', 'nas_delay', 'security_delay', 'late_aircraft_delay']
df_delays = df.groupby('carrier_name')[delay_columns].sum()

# Calculate the total delay for each airline
df_delays['total_delay'] = df_delays.sum(axis=1)

# Sort airlines by total delay in descending order
sorted_df = df_delays.sort_values(by='total_delay', ascending=False)

# Create a bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(sorted_df.index, sorted_df['total_delay'], color='skyblue')

#call the function to label the figure
label_plots('Airlines','Total Delays','Total Delays by Airline')

plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()

  • Southwest Airlines Co. had the highest total delayed flights among all airlines

plt.suptitle('Arrival_delay by Delay cause per airline', size=16);

Observations:¶

  • Late Aircraft seems to be the major factor for delays, but it might be biased as some of the data points are overshadowed. But based on the bivariate exploration, Late Aircraft is indeed the major delay factor.
  • Most of the curve looks like V-shaped, where the diagonal line (right line of V) represents the positive relationship, and vertical line of V represents no correlation.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • All of the airlines clearly have a high number of outliers (shown by dots outside the boxplot).
  • Late aircraft appear to be the biggest cause of delays, although this may be skewed since certain data points are obscured. However, based on the bivariate analysis, Late Aircraft is the biggest delay cause.
  • For majority of the airlines, Bad Weather followed by Late Aircraft cause longer delays.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

  • The majority of the curve in the Arrival delay by delay cause plot is V-shaped, with the diagonal line (right line of V) representing a positive association and the vertical line of V representing a lack of correlation.

Conclusions¶

  • In this project, airline delays are explored. Data revealed that only 3.4% flights are cancelled due to weather while most of them are cancelled due to late air craft (35.9%). Also, contribution of bad weather is only 5.20% to the delay of airlines.Also, flights are delayed due to security has low contribution. Southwest Airlines Co. has the most delayed flights among all. Also, correlation value between arrival delay and other features revealed that late_aircraft_delay has high positive correlation. Thus, this exploration can play a vital role while investigating the airplane delays and the respective authorities can take necessary actions to increase the efficiency of their service.
